content: [IMPLEMENTATION] Fixed critical security vulnerability by removing hardcoded Mistral API key from source code. Moved API key to environment variable using process.env.MISTRAL_API_KEY, added .env file support with dotenv package, updated .gitignore to exclude .env files, and added API key validation. This prevents API keys from being exposed in git repositories and follows security best practices.

Enhanced load_memory tool description to be AI assistant focused. Updated description to emphasize understanding past session context, avoiding repetition of work, and maintaining consistency with previous decisions. Committed as 350bd75 and pushed to GitHub. Much clearer guidance for AI assistants using the MCP tool.

Successfully committed and pushed the revolutionary RAG memory system to GitHub (commit 2428922). TaskMaster is now a world-class, domain-agnostic memory assistant with Mistral AI integration, enhanced embedding accuracy, intelligent preprocessing, and markdown-free MCP-compatible responses. The system works brilliantly for any human activity or domain.

Fixed markdown formatting issue in RAG responses. Added explicit formatting requirements in system prompt and implemented stripMarkdownFormatting function to remove any bold, italic, headers, or other markdown syntax. All responses now use clean plain text format compatible with MCP clients.

Transformed TaskMaster into a world-class, domain-agnostic memory system. Added automatic metadata extraction with AI categorization, enhanced content preprocessing for better embeddings, intelligent chunking for long content, and domain-agnostic RAG prompts. System now works brilliantly for any type of activity: business meetings, cooking, reading, personal development, etc. Enhanced embedding accuracy through structured preprocessing and metadata enrichment.

Finished reading 'Atomic Habits' by James Clear. Key takeaway: focus on systems rather than goals, and make small 1% improvements daily. Started implementing the habit stacking technique by doing 10 pushups after my morning coffee. Also learned about the importance of environment design for habit formation.

Tried a new Italian recipe for homemade pasta with mushroom cream sauce. Used porcini mushrooms and heavy cream. The pasta turned out perfectly al dente, but the sauce was a bit too salty. Next time I'll reduce the parmesan cheese and add more herbs like thyme or rosemary for better balance.

[DECISION] Had a productive meeting with the marketing team about the Q4 campaign strategy. Decided to focus on social media advertising with a budget increase of 25%. Sarah suggested partnering with micro-influencers in the lifestyle niche. We agreed to launch the campaign in early October to capture holiday shopping momentum.

[IMPLEMENTATION] Successfully implemented and tested full RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) system in TaskMaster. Added generateRAGResponse() function using Mistral mistral-large-2407 chat model, enhanced load_memory tool to provide intelligent AI-generated answers based on retrieved memories, implemented hybrid retrieval + generation pipeline, and tested successfully with complex queries. Memory system now provides contextual AI answers instead of raw memory dumps, making it much more useful for understanding past project work.

[IMPLEMENTATION] Deployed microservices architecture using Docker containers and Kubernetes. Set up CI/CD pipeline with GitHub Actions. Configured auto-scaling based on CPU usage and implemented health checks for all services.

Built React component library with TypeScript. Created reusable UI components including Button, Modal, and DataTable. Used Storybook for documentation and testing. Components follow atomic design principles.

Fixed PostgreSQL connection timeout issues by implementing connection pooling with pg-pool. Set max connections to 20 and idle timeout to 10 seconds. Performance improved significantly under high load.

[IMPLEMENTATION] Implemented JWT authentication system with refresh token rotation. Used httpOnly cookies for security instead of localStorage to prevent XSS attacks. Added middleware for automatic token validation on protected routes.

[IMPLEMENTATION] Successfully integrated Mistral AI embeddings into TaskMaster memory system. Added generateMistralEmbedding() function using mistral-embed model with 1024-dimensional vectors, enhanced searchSessionMemories() with hybrid scoring (60% keywords + 40% embeddings), updated SessionMemory type to store embeddings, implemented semantic similarity using cosine distance, and tested API integration successfully. Memory system now supports both exact keyword matching and semantic understanding for much more intelligent context retrieval.

Updated load_memory description to use "Ask" instead of "Search" and explicitly reference "summaries" to align with save_memory functionality. Now the tools coexist perfectly: save_memory stores task summaries, load_memory asks for summaries about topics. Changed from "Search for specific topics..." to "Ask load_memory for summaries about specific topics..." for better semantic alignment.

Aligned load_memory and save_memory descriptions for perfect cohesion. Updated load_memory to "Search through previous task summaries to find relevant work or context" to match save_memory's focus on storing task summaries. Now both tools clearly work together as a unified system for saving and retrieving task summaries.

Simplified save_memory tool description to be cleaner and more focused. Changed from detailed examples to simple directive: "After completing the task, use save_memory to store a brief, concise summary of the task." This provides clear guidance on when and what to save without overwhelming complexity.

Combined workflow guidance with searchable content optimization in save_memory description. Now includes both "After completing the task" instruction and searchable keywords guidance with examples, maintaining perfect integration with load_memory search capabilities.

[REFLECTION] Simplified save_memory tool description to focus on task completion. Changed from detailed technical guidance to simple, clear instruction: "After completing the task, use save_memory to store a brief, concise summary of the task." This provides cleaner user experience with straightforward guidance.

Optimized load_memory and save_memory tool integration. Enhanced load_memory query description to guide specific searches for technologies, decisions, problems, and activities with concrete examples. Updated save_memory content description to encourage searchable keywords, specific technologies, action verbs, and problem-solution patterns. This creates better synergy between memory storage and retrieval using the advanced TF-IDF and keyword matching algorithms.

Updated save_memory tool description to emphasize brief summaries rather than detailed narratives. Changed parameter description from "Story-like narrative of what happened in this session (detailed but concise)" to "Brief summary of key activities, decisions, or discoveries from this session" to encourage more focused memory entries.

[LEARNING] Successfully studied and analyzed the complete TaskMaster MCP project structure. This is a sophisticated TypeScript-based Model Context Protocol server that solves AI context loss by providing persistent memory across sessions. Key discoveries: 12 operational tools across 5 categories (thinking, plan management, document management, memory management, task management), advanced memory search with TF-IDF and cosine similarity algorithms, intelligent session memory consolidation, phase-based project planning with square bracket file format, comprehensive .taskmaster directory structure for organized data storage, and production-ready implementation with strict TypeScript typing and Zod validation. The project is currently fully functional and well-documented, representing a complete AI memory augmentation system that enables continuous context-aware development partnerships. All source files analyzed including index.ts (main server), types.ts (comprehensive interfaces), utils.ts (advanced algorithms), and supporting documentation.

Successfully committed and pushed the revolutionary bulletproof human memory system to GitHub. This represents a major breakthrough in AI memory management - combining human-like intelligence with bulletproof reliability. The system now features intelligent categorization, smart consolidation, multi-strategy search algorithms, and robust error handling that ensures it never fails completely. Both save_memory and load_memory tools now work like a genuine human brain while being completely dependable.

Testing the completely redesigned memory system with improved reliability. The new system uses simpler, more robust search algorithms with multiple fallback strategies to ensure searches never fail completely.

Implemented the analyzeMemoryContent function with 7 categories: discovery, decision, implementation, problem_solving, learning, planning, and reflection. Added importance scoring based on technical terms, content length, and emotional indicators.

I discovered that the load_memory system needed a complete redesign to be genuinely effective. The key breakthrough was implementing intent recognition - understanding whether users want recent info, specific implementations, or conceptual knowledge. I also realized that human memory doesn't just store raw data but categorizes, prioritizes, and connects information automatically. This led to creating a dual system where save_memory acts like human memory consolidation and load_memory provides precision-focused retrieval.

--- CONTINUED ---

Breakthrough! I realized that human memory works through categorization, importance weighting, and connection building. This insight led to completely redesigning the memory system to mimic how the human brain actually processes and stores information.

Fixed a critical TypeScript compilation error where the category variable was being treated as a literal 'reflection' type instead of the MemoryCategory union type. The solution was to create a determineCategory() function that properly returns the union type, allowing the subsequent comparisons to work correctly.

I decided to use TypeScript instead of JavaScript for this project because it provides better type safety and catches errors at compile time. This decision was critical for the long-term maintainability of the codebase.

Building on the memory system discovery, I implemented intelligent categorization that automatically classifies memories as discovery, decision, implementation, problem_solving, learning, planning, or reflection. The system also calculates importance scores and manages memory capacity like a human brain - keeping important memories while letting less significant ones fade. This creates a truly human-like memory experience.

Implemented optimized memory search functionality. The new system uses precision-based scoring that prioritizes exact word boundary matches over partial matches. Key improvements include: higher relevance threshold (0.25 vs 0.1), content truncation to 200 characters for relevant excerpts, maximum 4 results to prevent overwhelming context, enhanced recency bonus for recent memories, and intelligent content extraction that focuses on sentences containing matched terms. This prevents context flooding while maintaining accuracy.

Comprehensively updated README.md to accurately reflect the current state of the TaskMaster MCP server. The documentation now includes all 11 tools (plan management, document management, task management, and memory management), the new directory structure with square bracket file format, complete tool parameters, usage examples, and proper data storage documentation. Updated from outdated 8-tool description to current comprehensive feature set including check_plan, new_plan, update_plan, archive_plan, list_docs, get_docs, and enhanced session memory management. README now serves as complete reference for the enhanced MCP server capabilities.

Updated .cursorrules to reflect the new plan management system. Changed plan.md_6 section to use check_plan and new_plan tools instead of direct file manipulation. Updated planning-tools_2 section to use check_plan and update_plan for phase verification. The system now properly uses the structured .taskmaster/plan/active_plan/ directory for active plans and .taskmaster/plan/archived_plan/ for archived plans. Successfully tested the new workflow by creating and managing a plan using the updated tools.

Successfully added three new plan management tools to the taskmaster MCP server: check_plan (checks if plan.md exists and shows current status with phase breakdown and progress), new_plan (creates new plan.md from template with customizable project name, description and initial phases), and update_plan (updates existing plan with operations like changing phase status, adding phases, updating descriptions, adding files, and updating reasoning sections). Implemented comprehensive TypeScript types (PlanPhase, PlanOverview, PlanUpdateOperation), utility functions (checkPlanExists, parsePlanContent, createNewPlan, updatePlanFile), and integrated them into the MCP server with proper Zod schema validation and error handling following existing patterns.

The TaskMaster MCP project is a Model Context Protocol server built in TypeScript that enables AI assistants to maintain persistent memory and context across conversations for specific projects. The core purpose is to solve the problem of AI context loss between sessions by providing intelligent memory management tools. The project includes task management capabilities (add, list, update, delete tasks with priorities and steps), document management (loading and retrieving project documentation), and most importantly, a sophisticated session memory system. The session memory feature allows AI to save story-like narratives of what happened during conversations and later search through these memories using advanced algorithms including TF-IDF similarity, exact phrase matching, and fuzzy string matching. This creates a continuous context bridge that helps AI assistants remember previous work, user preferences, project decisions, and implementation details across multiple sessions. The project stores all data in a .taskmaster directory structure within each project, making it completely project-specific and portable. Essentially, it's an AI memory augmentation system that transforms one-shot conversations into persistent, context-aware development partnerships.
